## Centralized patch management process

Oracle Linux Manager (previously Oracle Spacewalk) is used to apply OS patches on the servers.

### Oracle Spacewalk

The environment uses **Oracle Linux 7**, a distribution compiled from the Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) source code. It uses the **Unbreakable Enterprise Kernel (UEK)**, based on mainline Linux kernel versions with Oracle's enhancements.

As a centralized OS management service, the organization uses **Spacewalk 2.7** to automate patching and software management. Spacewalk is an open-source systems-management solution licensed under the GNU GPL v2.

Different software channels are created in Spacewalk; each channel is associated with at least one repository that defines the source of packages and errata.

The **Unbreakable Linux Network (ULN)** is the resource for Oracle Unbreakable Linux support subscribers, offering access to Linux software patches, updates, and fixes. Credentials are provided in the `/etc/rhn/spacewalk-repo-sync/uln.conf` file on the Spacewalk server.

- **ULN** provides an `olN_arch_latest` (e.g. `ol6_x86_64_latest`) repository, which includes all packages for an Oracle Linux release, plus base and patch channels for each update of a release.
- **Oracle Yum Server** provides a `public_olN_latest` repository, which includes all packages for an entire release, plus a `public_olN_un_base` repository for each update. Unlike ULN, the Oracle Yum Server does not provide patch channels for updates.

Oracle releases security advisories (**ELSA**) for Oracle Linux as patches become available, published at <https://linux.oracle.com/security/>. Oracle also publishes **Oracle Linux Bulletins** quarterly, listing all CVEs resolved and announced in Oracle Linux Security Advisories. Bulletins are published on the same day as Oracle Critical Patch Updates and are updated for the following two months to cover CVEs resolved in that window; they may also be updated for fixes deemed too critical to wait for the next scheduled publication.

Oracle categorizes its security advisories as: **Security (Critical)**, **Security (Important)**, **Security (Moderate)**, **Security (Low)**, **Bug Fixes**, and **Enhancements**, quantifying CVE severity based on CVSSv3.

### Applying OS patches

Spacewalk repository syncing is stopped at the beginning of the patching cycle to remain consistent with software/package versions across Test and Production. Patches are applied in the **BD** environment first; once developers and the SQA team confirm the patches perform well with the application, they are applied in **PPS**. After the dev, demo, and alpha contexts are confirmed healthy, patches are scheduled for the **secondary production site**, and subsequently the other site after site cutover.

Patches are applied with the **Yum** utility. Useful procedures follow.

