## Non-centralized procedures

### Server firmware updates

Oracle announces firmware update information for Oracle and Oracle Sun servers in the Oracle Technology Network portal, accumulated by server architecture and model. Each patching cycle, the portal is checked manually for new updates. A zipped update package is downloaded via Oracle support login, placed on the TFTP server, and applied through the ILOM CLI by executing OS commands.

- **Portal:** <https://www.oracle.com/technetwork/systems/patches/firmware/release-history-jsp-138416.html>
- **Login:** Oracle support login

### VMware updates

VMware product updates are available in their update portal. After authentication, the product and version are searched to list available updates. Available updates are downloaded as a zipped file, transferred to the appropriate server, and installed manually per the included instructions.

- **Portal:** my.vmware.com
- **Login:** VMware support login

### Oracle Virtual Machine

OVM is updated through the yum repository. A yum repository server is created (accessible over HTTP and HTTPS), then configured to mirror ULN channels containing packages required to upgrade Oracle VM Server to a transitional state and to a particular version, or to install outstanding patches. To receive notifications of new updates, one OVM server is registered to Spacewalk and the required ULN repos are synced.

### Storage systems

**NetApp:** The automated upgrade method validates the cluster components, installs the target ONTAP image on each node, then executes the upgrade in the background. Automated upgrades of multi-node clusters are non-disruptive. First, check the available update version, then download the software image from the NetApp support site to an HTTP server (a PXE server is used to host the image). In ONTAP System Manager, go to **Configuration → Cluster Update**, click **Add from server**, enter the URL of the HTTP server hosting the image, click **Validate** to run pre-update checks, then **Next → Update**.

- **Portal:** <https://aiq.netapp.com/>
- **Login:** NetApp support login

**Oracle ZS3:** ZS3 controllers provide HA in active-standby mode, so the OS/firmware of one controller is upgraded at a time, then a "takeover" moves activity to the other controller for its upgrade. Navigate to **Configuration → Cluster** to view status. To upgrade, go to **Maintenance → System**, click **Check now** in Software updates, **Download Entry** for any outstanding update, then **Start & update using this media**. Repeat for the second controller after taking over the active status.

**FreeNAS:** A single-controller storage system requiring downtime to upgrade. Navigate to **System → Update**, click **Check now**, select the stable release train, then **Apply Pending Updates**. The system installs pending updates and reboots automatically.

### Cisco routers & switches

Review release notes for the software image for any exceptions. Log in to the device and confirm sufficient space for the image; delete unnecessary files if more space is needed on the active supervisor module. Download the image from Cisco.com to the TFTP server, copy it to the active supervisor module via SCP, and display the SHA256 checksum to verify integrity. Apply the upgrade command, save the running config to startup config, erase the startup config, reload, then verify the running software version and install licenses to enable required features.

### Windows updating

Windows updates are managed by a dedicated server running **WSUS (Windows Server Update Service)**. WSUS downloads Critical, Security, Feature, and version upgrades from `http://windowsupdate.microsoft.com`. WSUS identifies clients from Active Directory; a user policy specifying the WSUS server IP and port is applied to client PCs through the appropriate Organizational Unit (OU). WSUS then provides updates to the client PCs; users install updates manually upon notification.

### Nagios

From the Nagios dashboard, click **Check for update** to list available updates. To install, log in to the Nagios host, switch to the `nagios` user, remove the old front-end HTML files from `/usr/local/nagios/share`, download and extract the update, enter the resulting `nagios-x.y.z` directory, run `configure` (specifying the group name), then `make` and `make all`. Verify the configuration and restart the service:

/usr/local/nagios/bin/nagios -v /usr/local/nagios/etc/nagios.cfg
/sbin/service nagios restart


- **Portal:** <https://www.nagios.com/>

### Cacti

Cacti is installed via yum, so pending or new versions are applied with `yum update cacti`. Check the service status and restart if required.

- **Portal:** <https://www.cacti.net/download_cacti.php>

### Fortinet

Two GUI update methods exist; one is upgrading from the local drive. Download the firmware from <https://support.fortinet.com/> (credentials required), search for the appropriate version, and upload it. Upgrading from the FortiGuard Network offers only a limited number of builds, so confirm the target version is available via FortiGuard before relying on that path.

- **Portal:** <https://support.fortinet.com/>
- **Login:** Fortinet support login

### Infoblox

Confirm the correct upgrade file with Infoblox technical support or via update notifications. After downloading and storing the file locally, upload it to the Grid Master: **Grid → Upgrade → Upload**, navigate to the upgrade file, and **Open / Upload**. For an HA Grid Master, only the active node receives the software, so re-upload if a failover occurs before distribution. Distribute via **Grid → Upgrade → Distribute → Distribute Now**, optionally run **Test Upgrade** to surface data-migration issues, then perform the upgrade with **Grid → Upgrade → Upgrade → Upgrade Now**. Take a manual backup beforehand (**Grid → Grid Manager → Backup → Manual Backup**); restore via **Grid → Grid Manager → Restore** if needed.

### F5 LTM

Download the target version ISO from <https://downloads.f5.com/>. Export the configuration of both nodes before upgrading (**System → Archives → Create**) and download the archive locally. Reactivate the license on each node if necessary — determine the service-check date with:


grep "Service check date" /config/bigip.license


If the service-check date is earlier than the license-check date for the target image, reactivate via **License → Reactivate**. Import the ISO on both nodes (**System → Software Management → Image List → Import**), then **Install** to a target disk/volume. Boot the node into the new volume (**System → Software Management → Boot locations**), set **Install Configuration** to **Yes**, select the current active volume as source, and **Activate**. After the node reboots, verify the version and config, release the offline state on the upgraded node, then force the other node to standby so the upgraded node becomes active.

- **Portal:** <https://downloads.f5.com/>
- **Login:** F5 support login